      "writtenOn": "2026-03-18T19:59:06Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "First of all, looking at the verification setup [1], it feels a bit hacky to me.\n\nWe clone Gerrit from a stable branch (`stable-3.13` in that case) and then replace the JGit module with an arbitrary change from JGit@HEAD (which is essentially what the `servlet-4` branch represents: JGit@HEAD with some dependencies downgraded).\n\nGiven the breakage we’re seeing, we would likely need to backport quite a few changes—most notably the major Bazel modules integration change [2].\n\nEven that probably wouldn’t be sufficient, since a number of dependencies were updated in JGit@HEAD and then merged into the servlet-4 branch.\n\nSo while this approach is technically doable, I would be a bit hesitant to introduce such a tight sync between JGit@HEAD and the JGit@stable-* branches unless there’s a strong justification (e.g. a high-priority issue).\n\nA possible workflow could be:\n\n* Fix the critical issue in JGit on HEAD.\n* Backport the fix to the JGit@servlet-4 branch.\n* From the JGit commit currently used by Gerrit@stable-3.13, create a dedicated branch (e.g. JGit@servlet-4-gerrit-stable-13), and backport the change from JGit@servlet-4 onto that branch.\n* Update Gerrit@stable-3.13 to point JGit module to the new commit from that branch.\n\nThis way, we keep changes aligned with the `servlet-4` line while still maintaining a stable branch tailored for Gerrit 3.13.\n\nWhat do you think? Happy to adjust if there’s a better approach.\n\n[1]: https://gerrit-review.googlesource.com/c/gerrit-ci-scripts/+/563181/2/vars/gerritJGitServlet4Pipeline.groovy\n[2]: https://gerrit-review.googlesource.com/c/gerrit/+/488984",
